<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_2source" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Interference in 2D</title>
		
					<subsubsection>
	<title>Activities</title>
		
		</subsubsection>

		
		<activity>
			<title>Crests and Troughs</title>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					
				</p>
				<p>
					The figure below shows two overlapping periodic circular waves, their sources separated by some known distance.  The solid lines represent successive wave crests and the dotted lines represent wave troughs.
				</p>
				<figure xml:id="overlapping-waves">
			  <title>Overlapping Circular Waves Figure</title>
		 <caption>Two overlapping circular waves.</caption>
		<image source="2Source-4.png" width = "100%"></image>
  </figure>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Locate several places on the diagram where two wave crests meet.  Do these points correspond to constructive or destructive interference?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Locate several places on the diagram where a wave crest meets a wave trough.  Do these points correspond to constructive or destructive interference?
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<title>Path-length Difference</title>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					
				</p>
				<p>
					The figure from above has been reproduced below, with several points labeled A-F.
				</p>
				<figure xml:id="overlapping-waves2">
			  <title>Overlapping Circular Waves Figure 2</title>
		 <caption>Two overlapping circular waves with several points marked.</caption>
		<image source="2Source-5.png" width = "100%"></image>
  </figure>
			</introduction>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						For each labeled point, determine the value of the path length difference <m>\Delta D</m> as a multiple of the wavelength <m>\lambda</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						For each labeled point, find at least two other points that have the exact save value of <m>\Delta D</m> as a multiple of the wavelength <m>\lambda</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</task>
		</activity>

		<p>
					The figure from above has been reproduced below, with all points with maximum constructive interference connected in orange and all points with complete destructive interference connected in black.
				</p>
				<figure xml:id="overlapping-waves3">
			  <title>Overlapping Circular Waves Figure 3</title>
		 <caption>Two overlapping circular waves with interference lines marked.</caption>
		<image source="2Source-6.png" width = "100%"></image>
  </figure>

  

	
</section>

